{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332893762/1930091001/0153.xml":{"full_text":"WREN, COX ARE\nLIONS SPEAKERS\nSan Benito, with a winning per\ncentage of 94 In the attendance con\ntest held recently, was the subject\nof a talk made by J. D. Wren, sec\nretary of the San Benito Lions club,\nbefore the Brownsville Lions at\ntheir regular weekly meeting held\nat the El Jardin Tuesday noon.\nMy. Wren in his talk told how\nSan Benito managed to maintain\na record attendance week after\nweek.\nA second speaker was Bascom\nCox, former president of the local\norganization, who spoke on Lionism,\nIts history and objectives.\nOne new member was initiated.\nCub G. W. Callahan.\nRolland E. Friedman spoke on\nthe Good Will trip to Monterrey\nwhich is to be held starting Sept.\n26. New members of the Lions club\nto sign recently were George Desha\nand G. W. Callahan,\nGuest today was J. A. Porter, of\nthe Leader Barber shop.\nClubs See Rotary\nConvention Film\nMERCEDES, Sept. 10\u2014The local\nRotary club was host to the members\nof the La Feria club Tuesday -at its\nregular noon luncheon, with six\nteen members of the latter club in\nattendance.\nThe local club has a record at\ntendance. just one member being ab\nsent.\nSupt. E. H. Poteet. of the Mer\ncedes schools, and president of the\nclub, presided. Following the lunch\neon, all went to the new Capitol\ntheatre, and there, through the\ncourtesy of Manager Hugo Plath.\nfilms of the International Rotary\nConvention at Chicago in June,\nwhich the local club had ordered\nwere run.\nOther visitors were Raymond Mills\nand J. L. Compere of Weslaco; J. L.\nFester and A. Wise of Raymond\nville, and J. Wilcox of Corpus Christi.\n$1 TO FORMER WIFE\nNEW YORK, Sept. 6\u2014When the\nWill of Loudon W. Swinton was filed\nfor probate here recently, it was\nfound that he had willed the sum of\n$1 to nis former wife. Mrs. Genevieve\nSwinton, of Elizabeth, N. J., \"as a\nresult of her gratefulness to me and\nher love for another.\u2019\u2019 His estate\nwas valued at about $10,000. in which\nhis mother and two sons shared.\nHEATHER SUMMARY\nThe weather continued mostly\ncloudy and unsettled over the west\nern two-thirds of the United States\nsince last report, while more or less\ngeneral rains occurred in Texas and\nscattered showers practically thru\nout the wetem and far southeastern\nstates. Temperatures continued\nseasonable to above normal thru\nout the country'.\nBULLETIN\nFirst figure, lowest temperature\nlast night; second, highest yester\nday; third, wind velocity at 8 a. m.;\nfourth, precipitation in last 24\nhours,\nAbilene 66 94 1 48\nAmarillo 62 82 .00\nAtlanta 70 90 .38\nAustin 66 96 1.42\nBoise 62 78 .02\nBoston 52 76 12 .00\nBROWNSVILLE ...78 94 .00\nCalgary\u2019 50.00\nChicago 58 72 .00\nCleveland 58 70 10 Op\nCorpus Christi .80 90\nDallas 72 88 .00\nDel Rio. 78 98 .00\nDenver 56 78 .00\nDodge City .64 76 .40\nEl Paso .64 92 .00\n*V>rt Smith .68 84 .66\nHelena 52 72 .08\nHouston 70 92 .01\nHuron 60 80 .00\nJacksonville 76 84 14 .02\nKansas City .68 74 .00\nLouisville 60 82 .00\nMemphis 74 88 12\nMiami 76 86 18 1.10\nNew Orleans 78 92 02\nNorth Platte .62 78 .00\nOklahoma City .72 90 .00\nPalestine 70 94 .08\nPensacola 78 88 .00\nPhoenix 70 98 .00\nPort Arthur 78 92 .04\nRoswell 62 88 .00\nSt. Louis.\u2022. 66 78 .00\nSt. Paul 58 72 .00\nSalt Lake City .66 82 .00\nSan Antonio 70 96 12 .00\nSanta Fe 54 76 .00\nSheridan 50 84 .00\nShreveport 72 96 .08\nVicksburg 76 94 .00\nWashington 58 78 .00\nWiUlston 54 74 .00\nWilmington 68 86 .68\n\\J$\u00aer\nwtule, tPieLfte\nhot\nHere\u2019S something new and\ndelicious. Heat Rice Kris\npies in the oven, butter and\nsalt and serve them like pop\ncom! What a treat!\nRice Krispies are the\ncereal that\u2019s so crisp it\ncrackles in cream or milk.\nGreat for breakfast, lunch\nor supper. Toasted rice!\nAt grocers. Made by Kellogg\nin Battle Creek.\nRADIO SLUMBER MUSIC\nOn* of the best loved features in\nVdio Slumber Music is now being\nAadrast nationally over the Blue\nP'work by the Kellogg Company even\nunday night at eleven o'clock East*\nm Daylight Saving Time. Enjoy it\nOf ether with Kellogg\u2019s Kaffee Htg\noffe*\u2014the Coffee that let* yon sleep.\nRICE KRISPIES\nREVlCf WOQK^\nI \u20acvut TPOOK2T THE LEFT BELOV 19 VEPY\nPRACTICAL FOP THE G\u00bbPL AT 9CU00L. IT 19 OF FLAT OPE PE\nWITH A BOLEPO OF TUBES\u2019AND 9TRA9S By REMOVING\nTHE- BOLEPO AND ADDING THE OOLLAp SHOWN IN THE\nCIRCLE IT CHANGES IT9 GUI9E COMPLETELY\n(4?n THE CENTER 19 A GOWN OF WHITE TAFFETA\nV'TU A VOLUMINOUS SKIRT OF FINELY PLEATED RUFFLE\nTUE PlGUT. j\nBLACK PANNE VELVET\nADOPTS PPIW0E9S* LINES*\nAND AOOC WPlSTLETS5\nEXTENDING TO ABOVE TUE\nELBOW.\nlufE yoke ano puffed\nBEEVES A*E OF BEIGE\nLACE\n1\nCOURAGE OF PEOPLE CURE\nOF BUSINESS DEPRESSION\nNEW YORK, Sept. 9\u2014(*7\u2014The\npresent business depression \u201ccan\nbe cured only by the courage and\nactivity of our people,\" said Rich-\nard Whitney, president of the New\nYork stock exchange, in an address\ntoday before the Merchants\u2019 associa\ntion of New York City.\nTaking as his topic \"trade depres\nsions and stock panics,\u201d Whitney\nasserted that the decline in securit;';\nvalues last fall was not cause of 1\nthe business slump but that It was\nion the contrary, \"the general real\nization of the dowmward trend in\n1 trade conditions\" which initiated\nthe break in stocks.\n\u201cIf the stock market did not\ncause the trade depression,\u201d he\nadded, \u201cit is clear that the stock\nmarket cannot cure it. Many people\nstill seem to believe that rising\nsecurity prices will forecast the\nend of the present period in busi\nness. That may be so. but before\nsecurity prices rise there must be\nconfidence that business has turn\ned the comer.\n\u201cOur natural resources are as\n*reat today as they were last year\nOur great business organizations are\nin strong financial condition, and\nour industrial plants are at the j\nhighest state of efficient develop\nment. Credit is abundant. With thf\nexception of the difficulties that\nhave arisen as a result of the\ndrastic deflation of commodity\nprices, the business horizon is clear\n\u201cWhat is needed, therefore, h\ncourageous and intelligent effort\nand confidence in the future of our\ncountry. We all know that the pre\nsent period cannot long endure; j\nyet. individually, many of use are\nhesitant and wish to wait until\nothers have had the courage tr\ntaka the initiative. I am confident\nif the great organizations of busi\nness men throughout the country'\nwill put their shoulders to the\nwheel, that the period of hesitation\nwill be measurably shortened anc\u2019\nthe reestablishment of prosperity ir\nthe United States will become ar\naccomplished fact.\u201d\nOver-production. Mr. Whitnev as- j\nserted. was the basic cause of the\ndepression and the breaking point\nwas reached last summer when the\nconsumption could no longer heep\npace with the enormous output of\nGoods. The most dramatic result\no? the unsettled equilibrium was\nthe stock market panic.\nTODAY\u2019S MARKETS\nNEW YORK STOCKS\nNEW YORK. Sept. 10\u2014/P.\u2014For\nthe fifth successive day. bulls con\ntinued to to edge stock prices higher\nin the early hours of today s mar\nket.\nIn the main, the price movement\nwas narrow, but trading was fairly\nactive. One block of 15,000 shares\nof International Nickel was taken\none point higher. Allied Chemical\nsold up nearly 5 points, and Lambert,\nSimmons. American Power and Light\nand Spang Chalfant gained 2 or\nmore.\nStocks gaining a point or so in\ncluded American Can, General Elec\ntric, Paramount. National Biscuit,\nKennecott, and Westinghouse Elec\ntric. U. S. Steel wa sinciined to\ncase for a time, but turned firm be\nlore midday.\nCall money renefed unchanged at\n2 1-2 per cent.\nN. Y. COTTON\nNEW YORK, Sept. 10\u2014Cot\nter opened very steady at an ad\nvance of 9 to 13 points on a renew\nal of the covering movement which\ndeveloped yesterday and which\nseemed to find additional incentives\nin the steadiness of Liverpool and\ncontinued small volume of hedge\nselling from the South.\nTrade buying was again in evi\ndence and there was some commis\nsion house demand on the advance\nwhich carried the market up to\n11.10 for new October and 11.53 for\nMarch or about 13 to 15 points net\nhigher. There was a little more\ncotton for sale at these figures ap\nparently. and there may have been\nsome local selling on a belief that\nthe rains reported in the south would\nbenefit the crop. There was no ag\ngiessive pressure, however, and the\nmarket was steady within 2 or 3\npoints of the highest at the end of\nthe first half hour.\nN. O. COTTON\nNEW ORLEANS. Sept. 10\u2014C.P>\u2014\nCotton opened steady with first\ntrades 8 to 11 points up In svmpa\ntnv with much better Liverpool\ncables than due. The market con\ntinued to improve after the start\non shorts covering and some trade\nbuying, the better feeling being help\ned by expectation of a bullish tex\ntile report for August. October\nIraded up to 11.13 and Decem'tr ts\ni 11.30, or 14 points above yesterday's\nclose on both months.\nAt the end of the first hour the\nmarket was a shade easier and trad\ning was quiet while waiting for the\nweekly weather and crop summary.\nCHICAGO GRAIN\nCHICAGO. Sept. 10\u2014/P.\u2014Con\nsiderable change in the character\nof foreign news, coupled with scat\ntered buying by commission houses,\nlifted wheat values here around lc\na bushel at the start of trading to\nday. Com followed wheat to higher\nground because of the bullish of\nficial government crop report ex\npected after trading closed today.\nWheat opened 5-8 1 l-8c net high\ner than yesterday's close, then eased\nfractionally from the best prices.\nCom started unchan j*d to 5-8c\nhigher and subsequently gained a\nlittle, but then held around steady.\nBoy Is Writer Of\nSea Mystery Note\nST PETERSBURG. Fla., Sept. 9.\n\u2014(tP)\u2014A boy with a taste for stories\nassumed responsibility today for a\nnote in a tin can found floating in\nthe water here Saturday that was\nbelieved to have been a distress\nmessage from the crew of the mys\ntry ship Commodore of Philadel\nphia, that disappeared thirty years\nago.\nCharles M Raphun, Jr., 11 years\nold. said that on Labor Day he\n.\u2019wrote the note purporting to be\nfrom the wrecked ship Commodore,\nand sent it afloat in a can which\nhe found on the shores of Tampa\nBay. Charles said he got the name\nCommodore out of a library book,\nbut did not know that a ship of\nthat name was associated with a\nmvstery of the sea.\nApril 6. 1901. the Commodore of\nPhilladelphia drifted into Brooklyn\nharbor without trace cf a skipper\nor crew and no clue to their fate\nwas ever found.\nROCHESTER. Minn Sept. 6\u2014J.\nP. Sullivan recently lost two court)\nsuits\u2014one to his mother and one to,\nhis father. Botn stilts grpw out of f\nan automobile accident which hap- j\npened In July 1929. The father won\ni $200. and the mother $5000.\nDEMOS SILENT\n(Continued from page 1)\npublic education facilities and sug\ngested the possibility of equalizing\nthe educational opportunities within\n.ounties.\nMoody Praised\nThe administration of Governor\nJan Moody was praised. Mob viol\n^..ce was condemned and reiorma\naou and rehabilitation of the peni\ntentiary system suggested. Need for\nmore eleemosynary institutions, es\npecially for care of insane and tu\nbercular patients, was expressed'.\nIt was suggested that the possibil\nity of a system of taxation on oil\nand minerals that would permit an\nad valorem tax cut. be studied.\nTouching on highways It advo\ncated a \"speedy and economic\nconstruction of a connected and\ncorrelated system of state high\nways. It did not mention the state\nwide highway bond issue, advocated\nby Mr. Sterling in the first pri\nmary.\n\"The fairest and most just man\nner of raising funds to meet the\nrest of highway construction is by\n;:ixes imposed upon the traffic\n:hat uses and enjoys the road,** the\nplatform said. \u201cWe are committed\nto the policy of meeting the C06t\nof state highway construction by\ntraffic taxes. We urge the legisla\nture to consider the problem of fi\nnancing the construction and main\ntenance of designated highways to\nthe end that the traffic alone shall\nbear the expense of such construc\ntion and maintenance, and that no'\npart thereof shall come from ad val\norem taxes on homes, farms, ranch\nes or other real or personal prop\nerty.\u201d\nWoman\u2019s Pleas Win\nSafety From Black\nHOUSTON, Sept. 10.\u2014(A*)\u2014A 43\nyear-old Houston white woman,\nmother of several children, who\nwas kidnaped by a negro late last\nnight on the outskirts of the city\nafter he had shot, slugged and\nrobbed her companion, Frank B.\nHorton, salesman, returned safely\nto her home early today.\nShe told of being forced to ride\nten miles from the scene of the\nholdup with the negro, in Horton\u2019s\nautomobile, and declared that she\npleaded with the kidnaper and he\ndid not harm her. The woman\nawakened a farmer living nearby\nand he took her home.\nHorton is at his home recovering\nfrom a pistol wound. The negro\njumped on the running board of\nhis car about nine miles from\nHouston.\nThe negro, believed to be the\nsame one who escaped earlier in\nthe night from Imperial State Farm\nNo. 1 near Sugarland. robbed Hor\nton of most of his clothing and\nseveral hundred dollars in jewelry\nbefore taking his car and compa\nnion.\nFASHION\u2019S LATEST FAD\nLONDON. Sept Fashion s lat\nest craze in London is tattooing,\nand many smart women are having\nbutterflies, bees, pansies, bluebells\nend caterpillars tattooed Just above\nthe knee. A w-ell-known local ac\ntress recently had a floral garter\ntattooed on her leg. Tattooing Is\nalso being used to hide marks of\noperations, or unsightly* moles and\nother skin blemishes.\nREFLECTION\nPARIS, Sept. 6\u2014The Rossini Prize,\nworth S720, given by the French\nAcademy of Arts for the best poem\nin the land of between two and\nthree hundred verses, hasn't been\nwon for three years. Possibly the\ncondition tnat all poetry' presented\nfor consideration must be \u201chonest\nand decent.\u201d has something to do\nwith it.\nThe National Junior Brotherhood\nof St. Andrew. Episcopal laymen\u2019s\norganization, will meet at Oberlin\ncollege. Ohio, August 26-29.\nAir Mail Schedules\n\nThe achedult tor the mail between\nBrownsville and Dallas ta announced\noy the postoffice department as fol\nows:\nSouthbound\u2014\nueave Dallas 7:43 a. m\nLeave Ft. Worth 8:13 a. m\nLeave Waco 6:20 a. m\nLeave Austin 10:23 a. tn\nLeave San Antonio 11:20 a. m\nArrive Brownsville 8:03 p. tn\nNorthbound\nLeave Brownsville 123 p. tn\nLeave San Antonio 4:13 p. m\nLeave Austin 8:10 p. m\nLeave Waco 8:13 p. m\nLeave Pt. Worth 7:15 p. m\nArrive Dallas 7:33 p. m\nThe schedule for the American all\nmall to Mexico City la aa follows:\nLeave Brownsville .8:13 a. m\nArrive Tampico .11:00 a. m\nLeave Tampico ...11:30a. m\nArrive Mexico City. 1:45 p. m\nFollowing is tne schedule for th>\nMexican air mall:\nLeave Mexico City 7:43 a. m\nArrive Tampico .10:00 a. m\nLeave Tampico ..10:23 a. m\nArrive Brownsville .12:53 p. m\nPol lowing is tne schedule on the\nBrownsville-Mara tien Route:\nLeave Brownsville ....8:00 a. tn\nLeave Monterrey .9:45 a. m\nArrive Torreon 12:00 p. tn\nLeave Torreon 1:30 p. m\nLeave Torreon .1:00 p. tn\nArrive Durango.2:45 p. tn\nLeave Durango 4:10 p. tn\nArrive Mazatlan ............4:15 p. tn\nReturn trip:\nLeave Mazatlan ..............8:00 a. m\nLeave Durango .9:43 a. m\nLeave Durango 9:20 a. jj\nArrive Torrecn .11:13 a. tn\nLeave Torreon .1:00 a. tn\nArrive Monterrey 3:10 p. n\u00bb\nLeave Monterrey .3:00 p. m\nArrive Brownsville .4:30 p. m\nPOSTAL RATES\nThe United States air mall postage\nrate Is 5 cents fcr the first ounce and\n10 cents for each additional ounce or\nfraction thereof. Letters mailed In\nthe United States for the points tn\nMexico take this rata.\n\nTrain Schedules\nMISSOURI PACIFIC LINES\nNo. 12\u2014To Houston. Ban Antonie\n1:10 a. m.\nNo. 14\u2014To Houston, 7:00 p. tn.\nNo. 18\u2014To Houston. Ban Antonio\nJ:00 p. m.\nNo. 15\u2014prom at. Louie, San Antonio\nHouston. 7 :30 a. m.\nNo. 13\u2014Prom Houston. 8:10 a. m.\nNo. 11\u2014From San Antonio and Bous\n-on. 9 53 n m\nSOUTHERN PACIFIC LINES\nNo. 319\u2014Prom Houston. San An to\nil o, 8:15 a. m.\nNo. 318\u2014To Houston. Ban Antonio\n:13 p. ra.\nNATIONAL LINES OP MEXICO\n(Matamoros Station)\nNo. 132\u2014To Monterrey. Mexico City.\n8:05 a.m.\nNo. 131\u2014Prom Mexico City. Mon ter\ney. 3:30 u m\nRIO URANUS RAILWAY\nProm Point Isabel. p. m.\nTo Point Isabel. 930 a. m.\n\u201cANYBODY\u2019S WOMAN\u201d AT CAPITOL\nRuth Chatrerton, Clive Brook co-starred in the Paramount\nRerun: \u201cAnybody\u2019s Woman. Paul Lukas in the cast\nRuth Chatterton and Clive Brook, co-stars of \u201cAnybody\u2019s Woman,\u201d\nopening at the Capitol Wednesday. Also showing Thursday.\n85-Year-Old Camp Found\nBleak North Unfolds Another Chapter Of\nMystery of Missing Explorers\nEDMONTON, Alta., Sept. 10.\u2014<&)\u2014Discovery on King William's Is\nland of two camp sites of the lost expedition of Sir John Franklin has\nadded another chapter to the story of long-missing Arctic explorers.\nWord of the discovery was received by radio from W. E. Gilbert, pilot j\nfor Major L. T. Burwash, Canadian government explorer on an air\nplane expedition to the region of the magnetic pole\nThe message gave no details of the find, but said valuable data con\ncerning the far north and the fate of the Franklin expedition which\nsailed lor tne nortn years ago.*\nhad been obtained.\nBurwish and Gilbert left Edmon\nton on August 23 for the purpose of\ndetermining the extent of the shift\nof the magnetic pole and to seek\nrelics of the Franklin expedition.\nBefore the radio message received\nyesterday, the last heard of Bur\nwash and Gilbert was a week ago\nwhen they were storm bound at\nBernard Harbor, a solitary trading\npost on Dolphin Strait. Govern\nment officials at that time believ\ned the flight to King William's Is\nland would be abandoned because\nof the lateness of the season.\nRelics Found\nTheir landing at Victory Point\nmarked the first time white men\nhave been known to visit King\nWilliams land durihg tne summer\nseason.\nSir John Franklin, a British na\nval officer, set out in May, 1845,\nwith two ships and a company of\n129 officers and men to discover a\nnorthwest passage.\nThe ships, the Terror and the\nErebus, were last seen at the en\ntrance of Lancaster Sound. It was\n14 years later that first informa\ntion of their subsequent fate was\nobtained. Later searchers found\nrelics and skeletons on King Willi\nams Island which established that\nsurvivors of the expedition after\nloss of their ships hail attempted to\nreach the Hudson Bay company's\npost at Fish river.\nIn a Cairn at Point Victory was\nfound an account of the expedi\ntion's movements before the aban\ndonment of the ships.\nCleveland Robbers\nGet $11,588 Cash\nCLEVELAND. Sept, 9\u2014Twt\nrobbers kidnaped Edward Kells. 22\ndepartment manager of the Telling\nBelle Vernon company, forced him\nto open the company's safe anc\nescaped with $11,583 early todav.\nKells told police he was about tc\ngo home after visiting at the horn*\nof a young woman friend when the\nrobbers halted him and ordered him\nto drive to the company's head\nquarters.\nSeven More Sign\nFor Monterrey Trip\nS.ven new members have signed\nfor the Monterrey Good Will trip\nto start Sept. 26. it was announced\nTuesday.\nThe new members are Mr. anri\nMrs. R. Duff Howard. Mr. and Mrs.\nJack Campbell. Hubbard Hevey and\nMr. and Mrs. W. E. Heaner. all of\nBrownsville.\nProfits from the city water and\nlight plant are providing a new\n$20,000 \"white way\u201d for McPher\nson. Kas.\nDAREDEVIL PILOT\nRichard Barthelmess takes the\nleading role in \"The Dawn Pa\ntrol,\u201d which comes to the Rivoli,\nSan Benito. Sunday, with a\nspecial midnight matinee at 11:30\np. m. Saturday. From the story\nby John Monk Saunders.\nO.E.S. Women To j\nPresent Comedy\n'Special to The Herald.)\n8AN BENITO. Sept. 10.\u2014A com\nedy drama is to be presented by\nthe club of past matrons of the\nEastern Star at the Masonic Tem\nple here on Thursday at 8:30 p.\nm. All members and friends are\ninvited to attend. They are re\nquested to bring a penny for each\nyear of their age, the funds to be\nused for the benefit of the local\nchapter.\nVance Dies\nNEW YORK. Sept. 9. i*y\nArthur Vance. 57, editor in chief of\nPictorial Review, died last night.\nHe had been ill for several weeks\nVance began newspaper work in\nBinghamton, N. Y.. later becom\ning editor of the Home Magazine.\nHe was editor of Woman's Home\nCompanion from 1900 to 1907.\nNO MARS CANALS\nPARIS, Sept. 6\u2014Dr. E. M. Anton\nIzdi, of the Maudon observatory,\nnear here, has astounded scientific\ncircles by his assertion that there\nare no canals on Mars and there is\nno possibility of their being life on\ntne planet. He belives that the\n\u201ccanals\" are caused by illusions of\nvision perhaps based on a few cracks,\nrifts and other line-like markings.\nhead\u201cwhirleom\nNERVES UPSET\nTexas Lady Took Cardui for\nMiddle Life Troubles and\nSays She Got Better.\nKemp, Texas.\u2014Mrs. Mat How\nard, who lives near here, tells about\nher use of Cardui, in middle life:\n\u201cAbout twenty years ago. my\nhealth was very bed. I was pass\ning through a critical time In my\nlife, and I suffered a great deal.\n\u201cI was not at all strong and\nmy nerves got all upset.\n\u201cI had hot flashes, and some\ntimes would get suddenly so faint\nI could not stand up. My head\nwould whirl, and I could not see a\nthing. I would have to lie down for\nhours at a time. I felt mighty bad.\n\u201cOne day I was reading about a\nlady who had suffered like I wna,\nand how she had been helped. So\nI made up my mind to give Cardui\na trial\n\u201cI improved so much, after I had\ntaken Cardui for a while. X con\ntinued the medicine for some\nmonths until I had passed the\ncritical period.\n\u201cI have recommended Cardui to\na great many people since I first\ntook It. I never hesitate to tell\nany woman about it.\u2019* m\u00bb\nj\nby Women\ns Far Over SOTfea!*ja\n(Take Thedfords Black-Draught]\nI for Constipation. Indigestion. I\nBiliousness. 25 cents a package,!\ni| ESS- Sept. 19\nShow Grounds SL Charles and\nFourth Streets\nAmple Free Parking Space\nDifferent Show From California\nt BARNES\nCIRCUS\nAND THE ADDED FEATURES 33!\n'ftSRSW'fBi\nPAGEANT OF PEKIN\nGreat Gretona\u2019s Sensational\nEuropean Hi.\"h Wire Art\nTWICE 0A11V?\u00ab PM. OOORSOPEN 1-7 PM\nGRAND STAND CHAIRS AND GENERAL\nAOMtSSiON TICKETS ON SALE\n_CIRCUS PAY\na* Cisneros Drug Stsre No. 2\n1042 Elizabeth\nCity Briefs\nWonderful opportunity for men\nand women. Hair and scalp treat\nment. If your hair is falling, if you\nhave dandruff or unhealthy scalp,\ncome and see us at Amaya's Beauty\nShop. 1235 Adams street. Phone\n874-J. adv. 11\nDickey\u2019s Old Reliable Eve Water\nrelives sun and wind burned eyes.\nAdv. (1)\nFifty feet new guaranteed garden\nhose, $4.45; water pipe, lumber,\ndoors, windows, at low prices. Sales\nCo., 3rd. and Fronton.\u2014Adv. 9.\nWe use Electrified ozone water\nexclusively. P. o. Cafe. adv. 14\nTry our Mexican dinners P. O.\nCafe. _ adv. 11\nRelief Airplanes\nForced to Return\n^NORFOLK, Va.. Sept. 9.-H/PH\nTwo of the three Diaces which took\noff from here today with medical\nsupplies for hurricane sufferers at\nSanto Domingo w$re forced to re\nturn an hour later because of thick\nweather encountered over North\nCarolina. The third plane, piloted\nby Major Roy S. Geiger, U. S. C..\nhad not been heard from shortly\nbefore noon. It was assumed here\nthat he was attempting to reach\nFort Brag*'. N. C., his first sche\nduled stop.\nGeorgia has 154 accredited negro\nphysicians.\nim\nSAN BENITO\n3 Days Starting Sunday\nG